        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Short, Welcome Season'' (editorial, Sept. 4):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Short, Welcome Season'' (editorial, Sept. 4):</p>
        <p>Your editorial was not only accurate in its assessment of the transience of summer, but also in its understanding of the beauty of this ''not-quite-summer, not-yet-fall'' month of September.</p>
        <p>I live near Newport, R.I., from July to October, deliberately staying beyond Labor Day for some of the very reasons that you identify as the attractions of this in-between season. Cord wood is stacked for the increasingly colder nights, and, as I walk by the farms and along the coast, I notice the gradual encroachment of brown upon green in all the vegetation.</p>
        <p>It is peaceful to see this simultaneous ''ripening and dying'' by which nature reminds us of the ambiguities and contradictions of our own lives.</p>
        <p>CORNELIUS F. MURPHY JR.  Middletown, R.I., Sept. 4, 2000</p>
      </block>
